<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n13104b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n13" href="#n13104b">N13 (VI.D.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n13all.htm#n13104b"> 104(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ferdia</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The charioteer was more than a mere servant. Cuchulain sometimes called his charioteer &ldquo;friend&rdquo; or &ldquo;master&rdquo; (popa), and, on the occasion of his fight with <mark>Ferdia</mark>, desires him, in case he (Cuchulain) should show signs of yielding, to &ldquo;excite, reproach, and speak evil to me, so that the ire of my rage and anger shall grow the more on me; but if he give ground before me, thou shalt laud me and praise me and speak good words to me, that my courage may be the greater,&rdquo; and this command his friend and charioteer punctually executed. <small> Douglas Hyde, <a name="SEGL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SEGL"><cite title="source">The Story of Early Gaelic Literature</cite></a> (1920) 47</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05043b" href="c5all.htm#c05043b">VI.C.05:043(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
